jaco.swing.autocomplete

Class Autocomplete<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.awt.Component
      • java.awt.Container
        • javax.swing.JComponent
          • jaco.swing.autocomplete.Autocomplete<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the completion data type to use in this Autocomplete
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.awt.image.ImageObserver, java.awt.MenuContainer, java.io.Serializable

    public class Autocomplete<E>
extends javax.swing.JComponent
    Autocomplete widget is used to auto-complete a user's keystrokes by providing self-defined, context-sensitive completions in a drop-down menu. It can be plugged into any instances of JTextComponent including JTextField, JTextArea and JTextPane.

    Autocomplete reads and parses the content typed by the user into a token based on a defined pattern (delimiter). The token is then used to query suitable completions from a user-defined engine called CompletionProvider. A CompletionProvider is used to connect to a data source and supply the drop-down menu's contents according to the given token and context. The drop-down menu is automatically activated when contents become available for the menu.

    The term "selection" is used to refer to the state when a menu item is being selected (or highlighted) while the menu is visible. The verb "accept" on the other hand is used when the user officially accepts the selection, thus completing the current token with the selected completion. Use ListSelectionListener to listen to selection change events and ActionListener to listen to selection acceptance events.

    When the Autocomplete menu becomes visible, it does not steal away the input focus from the target JTextComponent. The JTextComponent remains in focus and continues to receive key events, however if the Autocomplete has an existing key binding for the keystroke (e.g. the Up and Down arrow keys to navigate the menu), the key event will be consumed by the Autocomplete. In other words, the key events will be first redirected to the Autocomplete and if they are not consumed then dispatched to the JTextComponent. Use key listeners with Autocomplete to listen to key events when the Autocomplete menu is active.

    See Also:
    CompletionProvider, Serialized Form

      • refresh

        public void refresh()
        Causes this Autocomplete to reload asynchronously. After this method returns, a background worker is executed to re-read the token and fetch completions from the CompletionProvider. If an existing worker is already running, it will be cancelled first. Once the worker has finished, the autocomplete menu will be refreshed. There is no guarantee that the worker will run to completion as the execution may be interrupted by user interactions or exceptions.
